Here is a simple C++ function that uses a Markdown parser library (in this case, `pugl`) to convert Markdown to HTML:

```cpp
#include <pugl/pugl.h>
#include <string>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    pugl::Parser parser;
    pugl::Document doc = parser.parse(markdown);
    std::string html = doc.toString();
    return html;
}
```

You'll need to install the `pugl` library first. You can do this by running the following command in your terminal:

```bash
pip install pugl
```

This function takes a Markdown string as input, parses it using `pugl`, and returns the resulting HTML as a string.

Please note that this is a very basic example and doesn't handle errors. In a real-world application, you'd want to add error handling and possibly other features like custom rendering of Markdown elements.

Here's a more complete example with error handling and custom rendering:

```cpp
#include <pugl/pugl.h>
#include <string>
#include <stdexcept>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    pugl::Parser parser;
    try {
        pugl::Document doc = parser.parse(markdown);
        std::string html = doc.toString();
        return html;
    } catch (const pugl::Error& e) {
        throw std::runtime_error("Error parsing Markdown: " + e.what());
    }
}

// Custom rendering of Markdown headers
std::string renderHeader(const pugl::Node& node) {
    std::string html = "<h" + std::to_string(node.level()) + ">" + node.text() + "</h" + std::to_string(node.level()) + ">";
    return html;
}

void registerCustomRenderers(pugl::Parser& parser) {
    parser.registerRenderer(pugl::NodeType::Heading, &renderHeader);
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "# Hello, World!";
    pugl::Parser parser;
    registerCustomRenderers(parser);
    try {
        pugl::Document doc = parser.parse(markdown);
        std::string html = doc.toString();
        std::cout << html << std::endl;
    } catch (const std::exception& e) {
        std::cerr << "Error: " << e.what() << std::endl;
        return 1;
    }
    return 0;
}
```

In this example, we register a custom renderer for Markdown headings, which converts them to HTML headings. This is just a simple example and you'll likely want to add more custom renderers for other Markdown elements.

