Here is a simple C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <sstream>
#include <string>
#include <map>

using namespace std;

int countWordOccurrences(const string& filename, const string& word) {
    int count = 0;
    ifstream file(filename);
    if (!file.is_open()) {
        cout << "Error opening file." << endl;
        return -1;
    }

    string line;
    while (getline(file, line)) {
        istringstream iss(line);
        string currentWord;
        while (iss >> currentWord) {
            if (currentWord == word) {
                count++;
            }
        }
    }
    file.close();
    return count;
}

int main() {
    string filename, word;
    cout << "Enter the filename: ";
    cin >> filename;
    cout << "Enter the word to count: ";
    cin >> word;

    int occurrences = countWordOccurrences(filename, word);
    if (occurrences == -1) {
        return 1;
    }

    cout << "The word '" << word << "' occurs " << occurrences << " times in the file." << endl;
    return 0;
}
```

This program defines a function `countWordOccurrences` that takes a filename and a word as input and returns the number of occurrences of the word in the file. It opens the file, reads it line by line, and for each line, it splits it into words and counts the occurrences of the given word.

In the `main` function, it prompts the user to enter the filename and the word to count, calls `countWordOccurrences` with these inputs, and prints the result.

Note that this program is case-sensitive and does not handle punctuation. For example, it will not count "word," and "word" as the same word. Also, it will not count "word" and "word " (with a space at the end) as the same word.

